   <mods:abstract>A memorial to the King, presented by the deputies and nobles of Bretagne,
            has resulted in the imprisonment of the deputies and a dismissal of nobles from court
            positions. Among those dismissed is Marquis de Lafayette, who stands high in the eyes of
            the people, and is secretly consulted by the ministers. States General must be called
            soon, lest bloodshed ensue. Events in war between Russia and Turkey; return of French
            ambassador at the Hague; dispute between Pope and King of Naples. Silas Deane's
            letterbooks and accounts are offered to him for purchase, else they will be offered to
            Britain; advises purchase of the letterbooks, which contain some information that would
            be prejudicial to the United States if in British hands. New form of federal government
            is well received in Europe, and has raised speculation in the funded debt of the United
            States abroad. Suggests that every effort should be made to retain this debt in America,
            lest it later prove embarrassing to the United States.</mods:abstract>
